  "prompt": "To which class cin and cout belongs?",
  "response": "The cin and cout belong to the iostream class, specifically they are objects of the istream and ostream classes respectively. They are part of the standard input/output stream library in C++.\n\nMore specifically:\n1. cin is an object of the istream class\n2. cout is an object of the ostream class\n\nThese objects are defined in the <iostream> header and are part of the std namespace. They are used for standard input and output operations in C++. \n\nExample:\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n    int x;\n    cin >> x;     // cin is used for input\n    cout << x;    // cout is used for output\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, cin is used to read input from the standard input (usually keyboard), and cout is used to write output to the standard output (usually console screen).",
